info: This corpus is an automatically annotated version of data from the Parallel Bible Corpus (Mayer & Cysouw 2014) that has been reduced in scope for the purposes of crosslinguistic research. Metadata from the original PBC file is included in this dict for reference, as well as the license information and the automatic POS annotations. The first three characters of the filename corresponds to the ISO 639-3 code for the respective language. The `tagged` key in this dict contains a list of lists, with the first item in each sublist being the verse number (following PBC convention) and the second being a list of tuples in [word, POS] format where `unk` represents unknown tags.
license: This data is shared under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license, and can be used solely for research purposes. The data is a selection of non-contiguous verses from a translation for the purpose of crosslinguistic research. Copyright of selected verses of each translation is retained by the original copyright holders.
metadata: # year_long: In 2010 the Wubuy Shorter Bible was dedicated, containing Genesis 1-11, Ruth, Jonah, and the whole New Testament. The decision was made to discontinue further translation work as all the younger people at Numbulwar were speaking Kriol as their first language, and the whole Bible was available in that language. About a quarter of the Old Testament is past the first draft stage, and could be made available for future checking or audio recording if there was sufficient interest.

# copyright_long: The first Bible translation work undertaken was the Gospel of Mark (Len Harris) in the 1940s. In 1952 when Rose River Mission (Numbulwar) was established, Earl Hughes, the chaplain, continued with translation work. This is significant as mainstream opinion at the time was that the Aboriginal "race" was dying out, and Aboriginal people should all learn English, so Bible translation was a waste of time.
Later, with the Whitlam years, there was a strong push from the Federal Government for Aboriginal languages to be supported. The funding provided greatly helped translation work. In 1976, The Church Missionary Society sent a couple to facilitate the work at Numbulwar by assisting the local translation team. Different methods were used, including local speakers using a tape recorder, subsequent keyboarding of the text and working through the multiple stages of checking. One lady in particular did a massive work of first drafting on her own.
